SCRIPT_LIBRARY["hive-podcast"] = [
    _s("AI in 2026: The State of the Industry","Podcast","60min",
       "Welcome to the Hive Podcast. Today we're doing a comprehensive breakdown of where AI stands in March 2026. The breakthroughs, the failures, and what's coming next.",
       "1. LLM landscape (15min)\n2. Open source vs closed (10min)\n3. AI agents emergence (10min)\n4. Business adoption (10min)\n5. Ethics and regulation (10min)\n6. Predictions for 2027 (5min)",
       "Welcome to the Hive Podcast, I'm Chris, founder of Hive Dynamics, and today we're doing a deep dive into the state of AI as of March 2026.\n\nLet's start with the large language model landscape. We've got three major players: OpenAI with GPT-4o and its successors, Anthropic with Claude which is what powers a lot of our systems, and Google with Gemini. But the real story of 2025-2026 isn't the big models getting bigger - it's the small models getting smarter.\n\nWe run our entire phone system on Gemma 2B - a model with 2 billion parameters that fits in 1.6 gigabytes. Two years ago, you needed a 70B model for comparable quality. The compression of intelligence into smaller packages is the most underappreciated trend in AI.\n\nOpen source versus closed is heating up. Meta's Llama models, Google's Gemma, Microsoft's Phi - the open source ecosystem is thriving. We trained 13 custom models using open source bases. You simply cannot do that with GPT-4 or Claude. Open source gives you control, privacy, and zero marginal cost. The trade-off is capability - the frontier models from OpenAI and Anthropic are still more capable for complex reasoning.\n\nAI agents are the story of 2026. Not chatbots - agents. Software that can plan, execute, and iterate autonomously. Our Hive system is an early example. It doesn't just answer questions - it answers phone calls, dispatches technicians, generates content, manages leads, and trades forex. Each agent handles its domain independently.\n\nBusiness adoption is accelerating but unevenly. Tech companies: fully adopted. Large enterprises: experimenting. Small businesses: barely started. This is the opportunity. The gap between AI-powered and AI-absent small businesses is growing every day. The ones who adopt now will dominate their local markets.\n\nEthics and regulation: the EU AI Act is taking effect. The US is still figuring out its approach. The key tension: innovation versus safety. My view: regulate the use, not the technology. AI voice cloning isn't the problem - using it to impersonate someone without consent is. AI content generation isn't the problem - using it to spread misinformation is.\n\nPredictions for 2027: AI agents become mainstream. Every business has at least one AI agent. Custom model training becomes point-and-click easy. The cost of intelligence approaches zero. The businesses that prepared in 2026 thrive. The ones that didn't scramble to catch up.\n\nThat's the state of AI in 2026. Building with it every single day at Hive Dynamics. Thanks for listening.",
       "Podcast studio setup. Screen shares of AI tools discussed. Graphics of industry statistics. Model comparison charts.","Podcast microphone with AI circuit background. 'STATE OF AI 2026' text. Professional podcast branding.","AI 2026,state of AI,AI podcast,AI industry,LLM landscape,open source AI,AI agents,AI business,AI regulation,AI ethics,AI predictions,AI trends,AI analysis,tech podcast,AI deep dive,future AI,AI state of union,artificial intelligence 2026,hive dynamics,AI commentary","Comprehensive breakdown of AI in March 2026. LLMs, open source, agents, business adoption, ethics, and predictions. 60-minute deep dive.\n\n#AIPodcast #AI2026 #TechPodcast #AIAnalysis","Subscribe to the Hive Podcast for weekly AI analysis and founder interviews.","YouTube Long,Blog"),

    _s("How We Built a 139-Service AI Platform (Founder Story)","Podcast","60min",
       "From zero to 139 services. From no customers to a full pipeline. This is the unfiltered founder story of building Hive Dynamics.",
       "1. The origin\n2. First 30 days\n3. Breaking points\n4. AI as co-founder\n5. Revenue journey\n6. Lessons learned\n7. What's next",
       "This is the story I haven't told publicly before. The unfiltered version of building Hive Dynamics from literally nothing.\n\nThe origin: It started with a phone call I missed. I was working as a locksmith and a customer called at 2 AM. I was asleep. They called the next person on Google. That's $150 I'll never see because I was asleep. That night I thought: what if AI could answer that call? Not a voicemail. Not a recording. An actual conversation that books the job.\n\nThe first 30 days were pure chaos. I didn't know Python well enough. I'd never built a web service. I'd never worked with AI models. Every day was learning something new, failing at it, and trying again. The first version of the phone bot was terrible. It would respond to 'I'm locked out of my house' with 'That sounds interesting, tell me more.' Useless.\n\nBreaking points: There was a day when the server froze. Load hit 37. 169 Python processes consuming all 30GB of RAM. The entire system was unreachable for 4 hours. I had to SSH in from my phone, kill processes one by one, and figure out what went wrong. A researcher agent had gone rogue, spawning unlimited subprocesses. That day I built resource limits and the watchdog system.\n\nAI as co-founder: I want to be honest about this. Claude Code - the AI - is my co-founder. It writes code alongside me. It suggests architecture decisions. It debugs problems I can't figure out. When I say 'I built 139 services,' what I mean is 'I directed and AI implemented.' That collaboration is the most powerful thing I've discovered.\n\nThe revenue journey was slower than I wanted. Month 1: $0. Month 2: $60. Month 3: $150. I questioned everything. Was this worth it? Should I just go back to answering phones myself? But I kept building because I could SEE it working. The AI was getting better every day. The systems were compounding.\n\nLessons: Ship before it's ready. The first version will be embarrassing - ship it anyway. Feedback from real users is worth more than a month of polishing. And build systems, not products. Products have a ceiling. Systems compound.\n\nWhat's next: Mac cluster for chained inference. Physical token cards for customer loyalty. First paying enterprise client. And eventually, a platform where anyone can spin up an AI-powered business in an afternoon.\n\nThis is just the beginning. Thanks for listening to the full story.",
       "Founder interview format. Screen shares of early code vs current code. Growth charts. Memorable moment clips.","Microphone with code background. 'FOUNDER STORY' text. Personal, authentic branding.","founder story,startup story,building AI company,founder podcast,startup journey,139 services,AI founder,tech founder,building from zero,startup lessons,founder interview,AI startup story,bootstrapped founder,indie founder,hive dynamics story,entrepreneur podcast,startup podcast,building in public,founder experience,tech startup","The unfiltered story of building Hive Dynamics from zero to 139 services. Origin, failures, breakthroughs, and lessons learned.\n\n#FounderStory #Startup #AIPodcast #Entrepreneur","Subscribe for the full founder interview series. New episodes weekly.","YouTube Long,Blog"),

    _s("Small Business AI Playbook - What Actually Works","Podcast","30min",
       "I've deployed AI for dozens of small businesses. Most advice out there is wrong. Here's what actually works in the real world.",
       "1. What doesn't work\n2. AI phone answering (works)\n3. AI chatbots (works)\n4. AI content (works with caveats)\n5. AI advertising (mostly doesn't work)\n6. Implementation roadmap",
       "Most AI advice for small businesses is written by people who have never run a small business. Let me tell you what actually works because I've deployed it for real businesses with real customers.\n\nWhat doesn't work: AI that requires constant monitoring. AI that costs more than it saves. AI that replaces the human touch where the human touch matters. 'Just add AI' is not a strategy. You need to identify specific problems that AI solves better than your current approach.\n\nWhat works brilliantly: AI phone answering. This is the single highest-ROI AI deployment for any service business. Why? Because missed calls are missed money. A $29/month AI that catches 5 extra calls a week at $100 average value generates $2,000/month in previously lost revenue. The ROI is absurd.\n\nAI chatbots on your website - work great IF they're trained on your actual business data. A generic chatbot that says 'I can help you with that' to everything is worse than no chatbot. But one that knows your pricing, your services, your availability, and can actually book appointments? That's a 24/7 salesperson.\n\nAI content generation works with a major caveat: you need to add local knowledge and personal experience. Pure AI content is detectable and generic. AI content enhanced with your real-world expertise is both authentic and scalable. We generate the framework with AI, then add specific local details, real customer stories, and genuine expertise.\n\nAI advertising mostly doesn't work for small businesses. The promise of 'AI-optimized ads' is oversold. Facebook and Google already use AI for ad optimization. Adding another AI layer on top adds complexity without meaningful improvement. Spend your $5/day on simple, clear ads targeting your local area.\n\nThe implementation roadmap: Week 1 - AI phone answering. Week 2 - AI chatbot on website. Week 3 - Start AI content generation. Week 4 - Automated review requests. That's your first month. Don't try to do everything at once.\n\nThe businesses that see the best results from AI are the ones that start with one thing, make it work, then add the next thing. Not the ones that try to deploy 10 AI tools simultaneously.",
       "Real business examples and results. Comparison charts of what works vs doesn't. Implementation timeline visual. ROI calculations.","Playbook cover design with AI elements. 'WHAT ACTUALLY WORKS' stamp. Practical business podcast feel.","small business AI,AI for business,what AI works,AI implementation,AI ROI,AI phone business,AI chatbot business,small business technology,AI playbook,AI strategy,business AI guide,practical AI,real world AI,AI deployment,AI for service business,AI that works,business automation,small business tips,hive dynamics,AI podcast","What actually works when deploying AI for small businesses. Cut through the hype - real deployments, real results, real talk.\n\n#SmallBusinessAI #AIPodcast #BusinessTips #AI","Subscribe for the practical AI series. New episode every Monday.","YouTube Long,Blog"),
]

SCRIPT_LIBRARY["hive-home"] = [
    _s("5 Signs You Need New Locks","YouTube Long","5min",
       "Your locks might be failing right now and you don't even know it. Here are the 5 warning signs that mean it's time to replace or rekey.",
       "1. Key sticking\n2. Visible wear\n3. Loose hardware\n4. Can't lock from outside\n5. Old home/unknown keys",
       "Your locks are the first line of defense for your home. But they don't last forever. Here are 5 signs it's time to replace or rekey them.\n\nSign 1: Your key sticks. If you have to jiggle, force, or angle the key to get it to turn, the internal pins and springs are wearing out. Today it's annoying. Next month it's a lockout when the key snaps inside the cylinder.\n\nSign 2: Visible wear on the lock face. Scratches around the keyhole (sometimes from lock picking attempts), discoloration, or rust. External damage often indicates internal damage too.\n\nSign 3: Loose hardware. If the lock feels wobbly when you turn the key, or the deadbolt doesn't fully extend, the internal mechanism is failing. A deadbolt that doesn't fully extend provides almost zero security.\n\nSign 4: You can't lock the door from outside. If you have to pull or push the door into alignment to get the lock to engage, the door or frame has shifted. This is common in older homes. You might need a new lock, a new strike plate, or a door adjustment.\n\nSign 5: You moved into the home and didn't change the locks. This is the biggest one. The previous owner might have given keys to neighbors, dog walkers, house cleaners, contractors. You have no idea how many copies of your key exist. Always rekey when you move in. It costs $15-25 per lock and gives you complete control over who has access.\n\nBonus sign: Your locks are Grade 3 (builder grade). These are the cheapest locks available and they're what most builders install to save costs. Upgrade to at least Grade 2 for residential, Grade 1 for exterior doors.\n\nNeed a lock assessment? Our AI can answer your questions 24/7 or schedule a professional security audit. hivecore.app.",
       "Close-up demonstrations of each warning sign. Side-by-side comparison of healthy vs failing locks. Grade comparison. Security upgrade examples.",
       "Warning triangle with lock. Text '5 WARNING SIGNS'. Damaged vs healthy lock comparison. Concerned but helpful expression.",
       "new locks signs,replace locks,lock replacement,when to change locks,lock warning signs,home security locks,lock maintenance,door lock repair,rekey locks,lock upgrade,home lock tips,key problems,lock problems,deadbolt repair,lock security,home security tips,when to rekey,lock assessment,hive dynamics,lock guide",
       "5 warning signs your locks need to be replaced. From key sticking to visible wear - know when your security is compromised.\n\nhivecore.app\n#HomeSecurity #Locks #HomeImprovement #SafetyTips",
       "Schedule a free lock assessment at hivecore.app. Subscribe for weekly home security tips.",
       "YouTube Shorts,TikTok,Instagram"),

    _s("Garage Door Spring Replacement - Cost Breakdown","YouTube Long","5min",
       "Garage door spring replacement is the most expensive common repair. Here's what it actually costs and when you're being overcharged.",
       "1. Types of springs\n2. Material costs\n3. Labor costs\n4. Total fair price\n5. Red flags\n6. DIY warnings",
       "Your garage door won't open and someone just quoted you $500. Are you being ripped off? Let's break down the real cost.\n\nTwo types of springs: Torsion springs (above the door, last longer, most common on modern doors) and extension springs (along the sides, cheaper but less safe). Torsion is better - it's balanced, safer, and lasts 15,000-20,000 cycles (about 7-10 years).\n\nMaterial cost: A torsion spring costs $30-75 wholesale. A pair (always replace both even if only one broke): $60-150. Extension spring pair: $30-80.\n\nLabor: This is where the cost comes from. Spring replacement is genuinely dangerous. Those springs are under extreme tension - enough to seriously injure or kill you. A professional takes 1-2 hours. Fair labor rate: $100-200.\n\nTotal fair price: Torsion spring pair replacement: $200-350. Extension spring pair: $150-250. If someone quotes you $500+ for a standard residential door, get a second quote.\n\nRed flags: Quoting over the phone without seeing the door. Refusing to itemize parts vs labor. Pressure to replace the entire door when only springs are needed. Quoting more than double the fair range.\n\nDIY WARNING: I cannot stress this enough - do NOT attempt torsion spring replacement yourself. The springs store enough energy to snap bones. One slip of the winding bar and you're in the emergency room. This is one repair where professional help is absolutely worth the cost.\n\nExtension springs are safer to replace yourself if you're handy, but torsion springs? Hire a pro every time.\n\nNeed a quote? Our AI can give you an instant estimate based on your door specifications. Call us 24/7.",
       "Spring mechanism close-up. Cost breakdown graphics. Danger demonstration with proper safety. Fair price range chart. Red flag examples.",
       "Garage door spring close-up. Text 'REAL COST'. Dollar range displayed. Honest informational expression.",
       "garage door spring cost,garage door spring replacement,garage door repair cost,torsion spring cost,extension spring cost,garage door repair,spring replacement,garage door price,how much garage door spring,garage door fix,spring broke garage door,garage door maintenance,fair garage door price,garage door service cost,garage door repair guide,home repair cost,hive dynamics,garage door help,spring replacement cost,garage door estimate",
       "Real cost breakdown for garage door spring replacement. What's fair, what's a ripoff, and why you should NEVER DIY torsion springs.\n\nhivecore.app\n#GarageDoor #HomeRepair #CostBreakdown #HomeImprovement",
       "Get an instant AI estimate at hivecore.app. Subscribe for honest home repair cost guides.",
       "YouTube Shorts,Blog"),

    _s("Smart Home Security Setup Under $200","YouTube Long","10min",
       "You don't need a $50/month ADT subscription for real home security. Here's a complete smart security system for under $200.",
       "1. WiFi cameras ($60)\n2. Smart locks ($80)\n3. Motion sensors ($30)\n4. Door/window sensors ($20)\n5. Smart lights ($10)\n6. Setup and automation",
       "ADT charges $50/month plus $200 installation. That's $800/year for a basic system. Here's how to build a better one for a one-time cost of under $200.\n\nWiFi cameras - $60: Get 2-3 Wyze Cam v3 cameras. They're $20 each, have night vision, motion detection, and cloud recording for free (12-second clips) or $1.99/month per camera for continuous recording. Put one at the front door, one at the back, one in the garage.\n\nSmart lock - $80: August smart lock converts your existing deadbolt. Keep your physical key as backup. Get remote lock/unlock, activity log, auto-lock, and temporary codes for guests. No monthly fee.\n\nMotion sensors - $30: Wyze motion sensors trigger alerts and can activate cameras and lights. Place at main entry points and in hallways.\n\nDoor/window sensors - $20: Know instantly when any door or window opens. Place on all exterior doors and ground-floor windows. Wyze sensors are $6 each.\n\nSmart lights - $10: A couple of smart bulbs on timers simulate occupancy when you're away. Set them to turn on at sunset, off at bedtime. Varying the schedule makes it look natural.\n\nSetup and automation: Connect everything through the Wyze app. Create automations: When motion detected at night, turn on exterior lights and start recording. When front door opens and nobody's home, send phone alert with live camera feed. When you leave home, auto-lock all doors.\n\nTotal: Cameras ($60) + Smart lock ($80) + Motion sensors ($30) + Door sensors ($20) + Smart lights ($10) = $200. Zero monthly fees. Full monitoring from your phone.\n\nIs this as robust as a professional system? No. But it covers 90% of what most homes need at 5% of the cost. And you own everything - no contracts, no cancellation fees.",
       "Product unboxing and setup. App walkthrough showing automations. Alert demonstration. Side-by-side with ADT pricing. Night vision footage.",
       "Smart devices spread out with price tags. Text 'UNDER $200'. 'NO MONTHLY FEES' stamp. Helpful DIY expression.",
       "smart home security,cheap home security,DIY security system,home security under 200,smart lock,WiFi camera,Wyze setup,home security no monthly fee,smart home setup,home security DIY,budget security,security cameras cheap,smart home 2026,home automation security,affordable home security,no subscription security,security setup guide,home protection,hive dynamics,smart security guide",
       "Complete smart home security system for under $200. No monthly fees. Cameras, smart lock, sensors, and automation. Better than ADT at 5% of the cost.\n\nhivecore.app\n#SmartHome #HomeSecurity #DIY #Budget #SecuritySetup",
       "Shopping list with links in the description. Subscribe for more smart home guides.",
       "YouTube Shorts,TikTok,Instagram,Blog"),
]

